Male palp (Fig. 13
A-D
): cymbium approximately two times longer than wide (Fig. 13B). Both ventral processes of the paracymbium stocky and triangular (Fig. 13A), distal process wide and strongly sclerotized, lacking any branch (Fig. 13
A-B
, D). Dorsal apophysis flat and triangular (Fig. 13B). Terminal apophysis wide and membranous, wrinkled (Fig. 13A). Tegular apophysis sharp, with a wrinkled surface (Fig. 13A, 
C-D
). Conductor ending with a sharp sclerotized process (Fig. 13A, 
C-D
).

Epigyne (Fig. 14
E-G
): dark, with a pale area in the center (Fig. 14E). Scape short, tongue-like, marginally sclerotized (Fig. 14
E-G
). Spermathecae broad, ovoid, separated by about 2/3 of their diameters (Fig. 14G). Fertilization ducts short and thin, reaching the spermathecae with only one coil (Fig. 14
F-G
). Copulatory ducts short and thick (Fig. 14
F-G
).
